review: I thought this was exceptional. The complexity and connections of the characters lives and the premise of the happenings of New York City in 1974 madeI thought this was exceptional. The complexity and connections of the characters lives and the premise of the happenings of New York City in 1974 made me think that the author had some big JK Rowling grand plan for the book. I was surprised to read in the author’s note, (which also was exceptional), that the writing of the book happened to him, rather than him happening to the book. The following was from the Q&A at the end of the book:“It’s strange, but as I grow older, I find myself developing more optimism. I keep inching toward the point where I believe that it’s more difficult to have hope that it is to embrace cynicism. In the deep, dark end, there’s no point unless we have at least a modicum of hope. We trawl our way through the darkness, hoping to find a pinpoint of light. But isn’t it remarkable that the cynics of the world-the politicians, the corporations the squinty eyed critics- seem to think that they have a claim on intelligence? They seem to think that it’s cooler, more intellectually engaging, to be miserable, but that there is some sort of moral heft in cynicism. But I think a good novel can be a doorstop to despair. I also think the real bravery comes with those who are prepared to go through that door, and look at the world, and all its crime and torment, and still find something of value, no matter how small.” ...more

review: I think this is my favorite book of all time. It had the elements that are on my criteria to make a good book: lyrical, witty writing, with a touch ofI think this is my favorite book of all time. It had the elements that are on my criteria to make a good book: lyrical, witty writing, with a touch of social commentary and overture of positivity.I am stumbling upon it around the time of my 26th birthday which was precluded by a few months of unpleasant happenings. It inspired me to write down 26 things to do that (should) delight me over the weekend of my birthday. As I was beginning to dutifully execute the list of delights I found myself spectacularly pissed off. During my bike ride, I crashed and my new bike was inoperable. As I began my favorite trail walk, it began to rain. After taking the afternoon to read this book, I realized I was blind to some delights in the midst of my angst. People graciously stopped their cars to see if I was okay after the crash as my loving roommates were conveniently available and hurriedly came to pick me up. During my rainy walk I stopped by my favorite hand-pie place for relief from rain and they greeted me by name and even remembered it was my birthday in a few days! Had I not picked up the book, perhaps I would have missed the concealed delights. Since beginning to read this I can’t help myself from saying “delight!” out loud when even the most minor pleasure comes my way. Perfectly cooked egg? “Delight!” Waking up moments before my alarm? “Delight!”Everyone would be happier if they read this book....more

review: I have been putting off reading this book for a while. Although this has quite the acclaim, I could not bring myself to read it. I anticipated that itI have been putting off reading this book for a while. Although this has quite the acclaim, I could not bring myself to read it. I anticipated that it would be a compilation of stories about highly successful people and how their success could be attributed to their regimented lives. I thought the litany of stories would be accompanied by one off productivity tips that I would never do.I should have read it sooner.Clear combines philosophy with tactical ways to change behaviors. This book was the cause of some long reflective journal entries for me. Particularly about how our identities shape our behaviors. For example, because someone considers themself a healthy person they eat a certain way and exercise. When we change our self perceived identities our behaviors naturally change. Fascinating. I will be thinking about this for far longer than it took me to finally pick it up and read it. ...more
